J oachim de la Viana, governor of Monte-Video, sent forward with a detachment of cavalry to explore the country, having leaped from his horse on the summit of an eminence‚ and exa- mined through a telescope the city of S. Mi- guel, (a place inhabited by seven thousand Indiam, and famous for its magnificent churches and famous row of buildings‚) in his astonish- ment at the size of the place, exclaimed to the horsemen about him,-—“ Surely our people at Madrid are out of their senses, to deliver up to Portugal this town, which is second to none in Paraguay.” This he said, though a strenuous favourer of the Portugueze, whose party he embraced to ingratiate himself with Barbara, Queen of Spain. The six other towns—those of S. Juan, S. Lewis, S. Nicholas‚ S. Borgia, and S. Lawrence, were also eminent for the number of their inhabitants and the beauty of their churches, though neither of them was
